UPDATE: turns out the data needs to be produces as it comes in, followed by the aggregated result at the last item.

In this case a `scan` can be useful. But the main problem is that an addition message must be added at the last step. There are few ways, but it seems that in any case you have to keep it somewhere outside of the Flux flow.

One way is to utilize `doOnNext` and then `concat` it, like:

    private Flux&lt;Integer&gt; aggregate(Flux&lt;Integer&gt; res){
       Tuple2&lt;Integer, Integer&gt; last = null
       return res
           .scan(Tuples.of(0, 0), (a, b) -&gt; {
               Tuples.of(b, a.getT1() + b);
           })
           .skip(1)
           .doOnNext((a) -&gt; { last = a; })
           .map(a -&gt; { a.getT1(); })
           .concatWith(Mono.fromCallable { last.getT2() })
    }

I&#39;m not sure that `doOnNext` is a very reactor-like code, though. 

So it could be also using the `materialize` and handling the `onComplete` signal to produce the aggregated value:

    private Flux&lt;Integer&gt; aggregate(Flux&lt;Integer&gt; res){
       Tuple2&lt;Integer, Integer&gt; last = null
       return res
           .scan(Tuples.of(0, 0), (a, b) -&gt; {
               Tuples.of(b, a.getT1() + b);
           })
           .skip(1)
           .materialize() 
           .handle((s, t) -&gt; {
              if (t.getType() == SignalType.ON_NEXT) {
                  last = t.get();
                  s.next(t.get().getT1());
              } else if (t.getType() == SignalType.ON_COMPLETE) {
                  if (last != null) {
                      s.next(last.getT2())
                  }
                  s.complete()
              } else if (t.type == SignalType.ON_ERROR) {
                  s.error(t.getThrowable())
              }
           })
    }

